[8] Pakistan
Date: 7 Nov 2006
From: A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: On-line International News Network [edited]
http://www.onlinenews.com.pk/details.php?id=104399

National Assembly Standing Committee on Health has expressed grave
concern over vast spread of dengue fever and has declared the
measures taken by the District Governments for containing the virus
as insufficient. National Assembly Standing Committee on Health has
therefore directed Health Ministry to take prompt measures for
control of the disease.
This was decided in a meeting held on Thursday in Parliament House
under the Chairmanship of Dr Hajra Tariq Aziz, MNA. The Committee
was briefed by the Health Minister Naseer Khan regarding the efforts
taken by the Ministry to control and prevent of dengue fever. During
the briefing, he informed that 2286 cases of [suspected? -Mod.TY]
dengue fever have been reported all over the country till 31 Oct 2006
out of which 736 have been diagnosed [confirmed? - Mod.TY] with dengue fever.
He said most cases have been reported in Sindh and 30 persons have
died due to it. He said that the federal and provincial government in
Sindh has taken pragmatic measures on an emergency basis to cope with
it. He said that 9 new centres have been set up in Karachi.
Secretary Health Ministry Anwar Mehmood told the Committee that all
out efforts are being made for swift tests of patients on emergency
basis. The Standing Committee also directed that mobile laboratories
and hospital should be established in far rural areas for the help of
the people being affected from this virus and a media campaign should
be launched on TV and radio to create awareness among the people for
preventive measures from this disease.
On the other hand, National Assembly Standing Committee on Health has
expressed grave concern over vast spread of dengue fever and has
declared the measures taken by the district governments for
containing the virus inadequate. It opined that Health Department
must be taken back from district governments and handed over to
provinces as health is a provincial matter. [The] Health Minister
further assured the Committee that situation is under control and
Government is taking all possible steps for the cure and prevention
of dengue fever.
--
