[9] Taiwan
Date: 7 Nov 2006
From:A-Lan Banks <A-Lan.Banks@thomson.com>
Source: Taiwan Headlines, Taipei,Taiwan, 3 Nov 2006 [edited]
<http://english.www.gov.tw/TaiwanHeadlines/index.jsp?categid=10&recordid=101356>

The Center for Disease Control on Thursday confirmed the first case
of dengue fever involving a military serviceman on active duty,
making the 25-year-old man the 6th person in 2006 to have caught the
fever by traveling to southern Taiwan. CDC Deputy Director Chou
Jih-haw said the man, who has been doing his military service in
Taipei City since the beginning of summer, was likely to have been
affected when he went home to the Chienchin District of Kaohsiung
City last month [October 2006] between the 12th and 25th. He also
reportedly visited Fengshan in Kaohsiung County.
Chou said the man did not show any fever symptoms until he returned
to the barracks on 26 [Oct 2006], where upon he was immediately taken
to the Armed Forces Sungshan Hospital that afternoon. So far, the man
has not been discharged from the hospital.
Chou said the center was informed of the man's condition on 30 [Oct
2006]. A blood test confirmed he had contracted [dengue] type 3 of
the infectious virus. Immediately after confirmation of the man's
condition, the CDC and Kaohsiung health officials sprayed both areas
with anti-dengue chemicals [presumably insecticides. - Mod.TY] to
prevent the virus from becoming widespread.
At the moment, no other cases of dengue fever have been reported at
the man's barracks in Taipei, said Chou. However, the barracks will
not be declared completely dengue-free until after a one-week
incubation period, he added.
According to CDC statistics, Taiwan has reported 514 cases of dengue
fever since the start of the summer with 350 of the cases reported in
Kaohsiung City, 151 in Kaohsiung County, 9 cases in Pingdong County,
2 in Tainan County and one report from Taipei City and Keelung City
respectively.
To date, 2 out of 9 victims have died from a slightly more serious
dengue hemorrhagic fever in Taiwan.
--
