[10] Saudi Arabia
Date: 05 Nov 2006
From: Pablo Nart <pablo.nart@terra.es>
Source: Kuwaittimes.net 05 Nov 2006 [edited]
<http://www.kuwaittimes.net/Navariednews.asp?dismode=article&artid=1534008352>

Saudi media reported an outbreak of Dengue Fever in Jeddah this week.
Hospital officials have so far reported 4 cases of dengue fever in
Saudi Arabia. There have been no cases of dengue fever reported in
Kuwait. According to local reports agricultural engineer, Mohammed
Habib Bukhari, has warned against a larger scale dengue fever
outbreak in Jeddah.
He said stagnant pools of water left over by an abrupt, but severe
downpour last week were a fertile breeding ground for dengue fever
[virus]-carrying mosquitoes. Bukhari pointed out that some 40 swamps
around the King Abdul Aziz International Airport in addition to the
Mesk Lagoon, Jeddah's dumping area, and the stagnant pools covering
several parts of southern Jeddah were high-risk areas. Dengue is
caused by the bite of the female _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, [which
breed] in stagnant water.
--
